Background¶

Saving money has long been considered an important virtue. While there are some who consider saving an easy task, there are times when it is difficult to make the proper financial decisions, such as when one buys a car for the first time. Even with ride sharing and public transportation becoming popular in metropolitan cities the large majority of America still own cars, making such purchases inevitable. After all, the automotive industry is one of the most important revenue creating sectors in America.

Consumers buy cars based on a variety of factors including style, gas mileage, safety or emissions to name a few. Many trends come and go in the industry but it seems electric cars are a trend that will definitely be sticking around. The advancements in battery technology has allowed for electric cars to have similar range to vehicles powered by combustions engines while not requiring the trip to the gas station and producing zero emisions. Even with the significant advancements, it is estimated that one in six new cars sold in 2025 will be electric. This change to the industry leads to more options when it comes time to buy.

There are many factors to consider when purchasing a car other than initial price, such as fuel costs, miles per gallon (MPG), fuel type, average lifespan, brand, and model. These factors tend to confuse initial consumers, and many simply pick the car that is the most visually appealing, or the least expensive. In order to assist consumers in making better choices when selecting vehicles, we have decided to analyze a few important features to consider before a purchase.

The dataset selected is taken from the the official U.S. government source for fuel economy information and covers cars sold between 1984 and 2017. There are 83 parameters initially in the dataset with 39,505 observations. Both categorical data, such as the car Make, and continuous data, such as the Miles Per Gallon (MPG), are covered in the dataset. Given the significant amount of observations, the sample data may be considered a suitable representative of the population.

We propose that Japanese manufacturers place a greater significance on the overall monetary cost-to-savings ratio from fuel efficiency of cars than American manufacturers. More specifically, this claim will focus on the difference in fuel emissions, fuel economy and comparative monetary savings between major American and Japanese car manufacturers.

If we compare different countries of the world, definitely US would be one of developed countries that a lot of people are using personal vehicles. Beside a vehicle for every member of family, some persons have two or even more cars. Based on this fact, selection of a vehicle with suitable purchase price at first and then optimized cost for fuel, oil and maintenance is very important for a lot of US families. Analysis of mentioned parameters would help individuals and families to purchase an optimum vehicle for their self. It is obvious that a lot of Americans are in doubt about this issue. At first, it is required to mention that there are some trade-offs between parameters of interest. For example, people can purchase a price with higher price at first and then their fuel cost could be very low. Some great examples are hybrid and full electric cars same to Tesla which their fuel cost is very low. These types of analysis would be very useful and I think a lot of vehicle guys would love them.

Features Defined¶

We have selected the following features of the dataset to focus on:

  • co2TailpipeGpm - tailpipe CO2 in grams/mile for fuelType1

  • comb08 - combined MPG for fuelType1

  • cylinders - engine cylinders

  • displ - engine displacement in liters

  • fuelCost08 - annual fuel cost for fuelType1

  • model - model name (carline)

  • make - manufacturer (division)

  • phevComb - EPA composite gasoline-electricity combined city-highway MPGe for plug-in hybrid vehicles

  • youSaveSpend - you save/spend over 5 years compared to an average car ($). Savings are positive; a greater amount spent yields a negative number. For dual fuel vehicles, this is the cost savings for gasoline

  • year - model year

Additional note:

Since there are various fuel types included within the dataset, such as liquefied petroleum gas, compressed natural gas, ethanol 85%, hydrogen gas, and others, the charts containing the MPG data also include the MPGe of electric vehicles (EVs), since electricity is also a fuel that individuals pay for.

It seems that some features need to be described more. Especially normal audiences could not understand some features with these short definitions. For example, definition of youSaveSpend could be as following:

**youSaveSpend**: The label shows the estimated fuel cost over a five-year period for the vehicle compared to the average new vehicle. If the vehicle would save the consumer money compared to the average vehicle, the label would state, “You save USD x,xxx in fuel costs over 5 years compared to the average new vehicle.” If the vehicle would be more expensive to operate than the average vehicle, the label would state, “You spend USD x,xxx more in fuel costs over 5 years compared to the average new vehicle.” These estimates are based on driving 15,000 miles per year, for five years, and the projected fuel price for the year, which changes annually, and is referenced in the fine print.

These descriptions are very important for some people that do not have background information and understanding of analysis would not be possible without a suitable perception of these attributes. </font>

Something to note with the youSaveSpend field is that the more positive the number, the higher the savings. By looking at the youSaveSpend field in comparison to our other fields, we can quickly see a negative correlation with number of cylinders(engine cylinders), displ(engine displacement), and fuelCost08(annual fuel costs). To be specific, there is certainly a linear curve represented by annual fuel costs and savings. However, when we compare it to comb08(city + highway MPG), we see that these two fields actually have a positive relationship.

Usage of KDE in diagonal part of pair plot is a good idea.As we mentioned, name of attributes are not informative for audiences and even writers have used some descriptions in parenthesis.

Novel Figure¶

The following plot shows the average miles per gallon for all manufacturers by region since 1984, as well as the top 5 individual models by decade. The lines here represent the region-wide average for all makes, whereas the data points (the flags) correspond to individual manufacturers. The size of each flag is based on the ratio of MPG to displacement of the engine, larger flags indicating higher MPG per liter of displacement.

As we mentioned before, it is better to consider median instead of mean. Additionally, one great change to above figure could be usage of logo's of manufacturers instead of flag. It could increase data-ink ration for above map.

The first thing that stands out here is the fact that, in each production year since 1984, the top manufacturer in average MPG is a Japanese make, and the lower end are all American makes. The consistency of this trend is further demonstrated by the very near constant delta between the region-wide average MPG over time. It's also noteworthy that these American makes on the low end of MPG are also the smallest sized flags on the chart.

This tells us that we can't attribute the lower average fuel efficiency of American cars to the fact that Japanese manufacturers generally steer clear of making powerful cars with high displacement, which would naturally drive down their fuel efficiency. We saw from the boxplot of # of cylinders by region that American makes do tend to make more cars with larger engines, but in both cases we can see that Japanese cars are still more fuel efficient holding these other factors constant. Keep in mind, however, that these indeed are all averages.

Looking at the bar graph we can see that the top 5 models by MPG for each decade are more of a mixed bag. In fact, in three of the last four decades, the highest MPG for all models was acheived by an American car. Note that because some of these are electric cars (e.g, Chevrolet Bolt EV, Honda Fit EV), in these cases the units displayed are mpgE, or the MPG equivalent in terms of energy costs. This tells us that the technology has always been available to American manufacturers to make more fuel efficient cars, more so now than ever with the popularization of fully electric vehicles, but that they still on average tend to produce a higher volume of gas-guzzlers. Whether this is done to cut production costs, or simply because their consumer base values other features over fuel efficiency, requires further evaluation.

Conclusion¶

Based on the results, despite certain American models possessing a higher MPG than Japanese vehicles in recent years, the claim that Japanese car manufacturers prioritize the overall cost-to-savings ratio from fuel efficiency is consistent with the data, and thus valid.

We have also determined that the marginal increase in savings drops off significantly beyond 40-50 mpg. While vehicles with over 50-100 mpg (mostly the electric vehicles) do provide greater overall savings, the difference is minimal compared to that of a 20 to 30 mpg upgrade. This would suggest that, as a consumer, other features may be more worthy of consideration for any car with greater than 40 mpg. The fuel cost savings over a 5 year term also indicate that Japanese cars on average tend to have a higher cost-savings ratio than American cars.

Further parsing of the dataset, such as separating cars by petroleum/gas, hybrids, and FEVs may elucidate additional evidence to support or refute the claim. This is because hybrid and FEV vehicles tend to cost significantly more than gasoline vehicles, so consumers may need to consider how long it will take to receive a positive return when purchasing those types of vehicles.

Consumers wishing to save money may select a car with up to 50 MPG rating, but it is important to know that higher MPG cars may also suffer a decrease in performance as they tend to have a lower number of cylinders on average. Consumers should explore additional factors such as availability of fuel when selecting a vehicle.

At the end of the day, the selection of a vehicle is fully dependent on the consumer's income, lifestyle and needs. For example, an individual living alone may only require a small vehicle that could take them to and from work, but may want to purchase a high-end low-MPG supercar. However, a family of four may require a larger vehicle for daily transportation, but may be unable to afford daily fuel costs.

One type of diagrams that people like to see are time diagrams that show changes of parameters over the years. You could see one sample below.

from collections import Counter

def plotvar(consider, style='ggplot', size=(15, 7)):
    linestyles=['.-', 'o-', '^-', '-.']
    cycle_length=8
    with plt.style.context(style):
        plt.figure(figsize=size)
        count = 0
        for name, group in vehicles_df.groupby(consider):
            temp = list(sorted(list(Counter(group['year']).items()), key=lambda x: x[0]))
            x, y = [i[0] for i in temp], [i[1] for i in temp]
            linestyle = linestyles[int(count / cycle_length)]
            plt.plot(x, y, linestyle, label=name)
            count += 1
        plt.xlabel('Years')
        plt.ylabel('Count')
        plt.title('Evolution of number of Cylinders over the years')
        plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.3, 1.))
